<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,1047,1973]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1119,1144]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species had not been found with gonothecae since its original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Jaderholm, E." box="[1235,1423,1119,1144]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref42901" refString="Jaderholm, E. (1904) Mitteilungen ueber einige von der Schwedischen Antarctic-Expedition 1901 - 1903 eingesammelte Hydroiden. Archives de Zoologie Experimentale et Generale, Series 4, 3 (Notes et revue 1), 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="1904">Jäderholm 1904</bibRefCitation>
), and only male ones are known. Our material is provided with male gonothecae: 
<quantity box="[1097,1235,1156,1181]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="1.4" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.3">1.3–1.5 mm</quantity>
high, 380 µm in maximum diameter; very delicate, easily collapsible; cylindrical, truncated distally; with terminal, circular aperture (
<figureCitation box="[159,260,1228,1253]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1489,1511]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,198,1462]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1436,193,1468]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 14. a Halecium incertus: colony. b–c H. secundum: b hydrophore and hydrotheca; c gonothecae. d–g H. tubatum: d stem; e detail of the basal rings of the stem; f–g hydrothecae. h–j Hydrodendron arboreum: h stem showing hydrophores arrangement; i colony; j nematophore." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608555/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 14c</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Jaderholm, E." box="[283,486,1228,1253]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref42901" refString="Jaderholm, E. (1904) Mitteilungen ueber einige von der Schwedischen Antarctic-Expedition 1901 - 1903 eingesammelte Hydroiden. Archives de Zoologie Experimentale et Generale, Series 4, 3 (Notes et revue 1), 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="1904">Jäderholm (1904)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned a shallow distal furrow and a proximal sharp keel in the gonothecae. However, given the delicate consistency of the gonothecae, we regard Jäderholm’s observations as a probable artefact that occurred when mounting the microslides.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,1047,1973]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero, A. L." box="[199,459,1335,1360]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="243 - 280" refId="ref44359" refString="Pena Cantero, A. L. (2014 b) Revision of the Antarctic species of Halecium Oken, 1815 (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Haleciidae). Zootaxa, 3790 (2), 243 - 280. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3790.2.2" type="journal article" year="2014">Peña Cantero (2014b)</bibRefCitation>
revised the 
<typeStatus box="[617,715,1335,1360]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson, 2008" authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="2008" box="[767,1206,1335,1360]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="brevithecum">
<emphasis box="[767,1027,1335,1360]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Halecium brevithecum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Watson, J. E." box="[1042,1206,1336,1360]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="165 - 178" refId="ref47732" refString="Watson, J. E. (2008) Hydroids of the BANZARE expeditions, 1929 - 1931: the family Haleciidae (Hydrozoa, Leptothecata) from the Australian Antarctic Territory. Memoirs of the Museum of Fictoria, 65, 165 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.24199 / j. mmv. 2008.65.9" type="journal article" year="2008">Watson, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, discussed the few differences between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaderholm" authorityYear="1904" box="[381,527,1372,1397]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundum">
<emphasis box="[381,527,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. secundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="2008" box="[582,754,1372,1397]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="brevithecum">
<emphasis box="[582,754,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. brevithecum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and noted that the latter was described from scarce, infertile material mounted in microslides, and that therefore cannot be completely characterized (
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero, A. L." box="[1136,1368,1407,1432]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="243 - 280" refId="ref44359" refString="Pena Cantero, A. L. (2014 b) Revision of the Antarctic species of Halecium Oken, 1815 (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Haleciidae). Zootaxa, 3790 (2), 243 - 280. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3790.2.2" type="journal article" year="2014">Peña Cantero 2014b</bibRefCitation>
: 253). According to him, the hydrothecal adcauline wall of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="2008" box="[757,931,1444,1469]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="brevithecum">
<emphasis box="[757,931,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. brevithecum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is completely adnate to the internode in the 
<typeStatus box="[151,253,1479,1504]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">holotype</typeStatus>
. In the original description, 
<bibRefCitation author="Watson, J. E." box="[570,735,1480,1504]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="165 - 178" refId="ref47732" refString="Watson, J. E. (2008) Hydroids of the BANZARE expeditions, 1929 - 1931: the family Haleciidae (Hydrozoa, Leptothecata) from the Australian Antarctic Territory. Memoirs of the Museum of Fictoria, 65, 165 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.24199 / j. mmv. 2008.65.9" type="journal article" year="2008">Watson (2008)</bibRefCitation>
also indicated that the adcauline hydrothecal wall is adnate to the internode. However, she also pointed out that the adcauline wall of the hydrophore becomes free just below the hydrotheca. This imply that the hydrothecae might also be free. In this sense, a figure provided by her (
<bibRefCitation author="Watson, J. E." pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="165 - 178" refId="ref47732" refString="Watson, J. E. (2008) Hydroids of the BANZARE expeditions, 1929 - 1931: the family Haleciidae (Hydrozoa, Leptothecata) from the Australian Antarctic Territory. Memoirs of the Museum of Fictoria, 65, 165 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.24199 / j. mmv. 2008.65.9" type="journal article" year="2008">
Watson 2008: 
<figureCitation box="[221,301,1588,1613]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1875,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,272,1843]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,267,1853]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 4. a–i Tubularia longstaffi: a polyp-carrying tube; b male polyp; c blastostyle with developing male gonophores; d blastostyle with fully-grown male gonophores; e female polyp; f blastostyle with fully-grown female gonophores; g–h detail of female gonophores carrying actinulae; i actinulae in different stages of development. j–o Zanclea hicksoni: j early-developing polyp, k expanded young polyps, l expanded polyps with hydrorhizal filaments, m contracted polyp, n–o detail of polyps showing tentacle arrangement in linear clusters (arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608535/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 4c</figureCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
) apparently shows a free adcauline hydrothecal wall. It seems, therefore, that this character may vary among hydrothecae, as it has been documented for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaderholm" authorityYear="1904" box="[733,881,1623,1648]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundum">
<emphasis box="[733,881,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. secundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero, A. L." box="[935,1166,1623,1648]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="243 - 280" refId="ref44359" refString="Pena Cantero, A. L. (2014 b) Revision of the Antarctic species of Halecium Oken, 1815 (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Haleciidae). Zootaxa, 3790 (2), 243 - 280. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3790.2.2" type="journal article" year="2014">Peña Cantero 2014b</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero, A. L." box="[1188,1436,1623,1648]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="243 - 280" refId="ref44359" refString="Pena Cantero, A. L. (2014 b) Revision of the Antarctic species of Halecium Oken, 1815 (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Haleciidae). Zootaxa, 3790 (2), 243 - 280. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3790.2.2" type="journal article" year="2014">Peña Cantero (2014b)</bibRefCitation>
also indicated that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="2008" box="[388,569,1660,1685]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="brevithecum">
<emphasis box="[388,569,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. brevithecum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaderholm" authorityYear="1904" box="[918,1073,1660,1685]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundum">
<emphasis box="[918,1073,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. secundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the distinctly longer first hydrothecate internode of the branches, the presence of reddish stems, and the perpendicular arrangement of the lower-order branches compared to previous ones. All these features have been clearly observed from the reproductive material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaderholm" authorityYear="1904" box="[444,595,1767,1792]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundum">
<emphasis box="[444,595,1767,1792]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. secundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Being so, we consider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="2008" box="[889,1147,1767,1792]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="brevithecum">
<emphasis box="[889,1147,1767,1792]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Halecium brevithecum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of Jäderholm’s species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,1047,1973]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,506,1839,1864]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Ecology and distribution.</emphasis>
Previously reported at depths between 40 (Peña Cantero 
<emphasis box="[1171,1229,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al.</emphasis>
2013) and 
<quantity box="[1363,1436,1839,1864]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.02" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="m" value="502.0">502 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Watson, J. E." box="[158,528,1876,1901]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="165 - 178" refId="ref47732" refString="Watson, J. E. (2008) Hydroids of the BANZARE expeditions, 1929 - 1931: the family Haleciidae (Hydrozoa, Leptothecata) from the Australian Antarctic Territory. Memoirs of the Museum of Fictoria, 65, 165 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.24199 / j. mmv. 2008.65.9" type="journal article" year="2008">
Watson 2008, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson" authorityYear="2008" box="[355,528,1876,1901]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="brevithecum">
<emphasis box="[355,528,1876,1901]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H. brevithecum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</bibRefCitation>
); present material at 
<quantity box="[772,902,1876,1900]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.01" metricValueMax="2.83" metricValueMin="1.19" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="m" value="201.0" valueMax="283.0" valueMin="119.0">
119– 
<specimenCount box="[827,902,1876,1900]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="generic">283 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. Circum-Antarctic species (Peña Cantero 
<emphasis box="[1379,1436,1876,1901]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al.</emphasis>
2013), with only three validated records and a fourth pending one (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero, A. L." box="[999,1239,1911,1936]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="243 - 280" refId="ref44359" refString="Pena Cantero, A. L. (2014 b) Revision of the Antarctic species of Halecium Oken, 1815 (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Haleciidae). Zootaxa, 3790 (2), 243 - 280. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3790.2.2" type="journal article" year="2014">Peña Cantero 2014b</bibRefCitation>
), present finding constitutes the first evidence from the Weddell Sea.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
